<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>get out of it • snap out of it</xh5><p> <i>get out of it</i>—1. escape from a difficult or awkward situation: They wanted us to go lunch. I did my best to <u>get out of it</u>. 2. <i>(coll.)</i> is used to tell a person not to talk nonsense: <u>Get out of it</u>! You can’t expect me to believe that!</p><p><i>snap out of it</i>—(coll.) free oneself from a state of depression by an effort: For heaven’s sake, Lucia, <u>snap out of it</u> and act like a human being.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression is not antonymous in meaning to the phrase <b>snap to it</b>—(coll.) start moving or working quickly: I want those bricks moved; come on, <u>snap to it</u>!</p> </entry>
